\begin_layout Paragraph
Rescaling Inventor Flows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As explained in the main text, the measure of inventor flows aims to capture
 the strength of the connections between two sectors.
 I take several steps to ensure that I do not overestimate these connections
 and to normalize them to account for the size of sending and receiving
 sectors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a first step, I build normalized directed flows for each inventor 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in order to avoid double counting.
 For example, for transitions between sector 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, I define:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{flow}_{1\rightarrow2,i,t} & \equiv\frac{\sum\text{\ensuremath{\bm{1}\left\{ i\text{ moves }1\rightarrow2\text{ in }t\right\} }}}{\sum_{j,k}\text{\ensuremath{\bm{1}\left\{ i\text{ moves }j\rightarrow k\text{ in }t\right\} }}}\times\alpha_{i}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This measure attributes a fraction of the effective inventor fixed effect
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 to each transition in proportion to the number of overall inventor 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's transitions across sectors in each year.
 The first term in this formula is precisely the share of transitions from
 sector 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 to sector 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 relative to overall transitions between any two sectors 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 that inventor 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 took part in.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, I compute total inflows (outflows) for each NAICS 4-digit sector,
 summing over all years, inventors and origin (destination) sectors.
 For example, inflows for sector 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

are defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{inflow}_{1}=\sum_{n}\sum_{t}\sum_{i}\text{flow}{}_{n\rightarrow\text{1},i,t},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 denotes origin NAICS sectors, 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 years, and 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 inventor identifiers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Third, I proceed to compute the share of directed flows between each pair
 of sector as a share of total inflows or outflows.
 For example, the share of inflows coming from sector 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 and entering sector 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{share}_{1\ensuremath{\leftarrow}2}=\frac{\sum_{t}\sum_{i}\text{flow}_{2\rightarrow1,i,t}}{\text{inflow}_{1}}.
\]

\end_inset

 In this example, this measure captures the relative importance of inflows
 from sector 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 for the overall number of inventors received by sector 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 However, this measure can still overstate flows from large to small sectors,
 or vice versa.
 As a result, and since I need undirected flows to apply the Louvain algorithm,
 I define network edge weights starting from an average of the above shares
 of inflows and outflows for each sector and taking the minimum between
 the two measures as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
W_{12}=W_{21}=\min & \left\lbrace \frac{\text{share}_{\text{1\ensuremath{\leftarrow}2}}+\text{share}_{\text{1\ensuremath{\rightarrow}2}}}{2},\right.\\
 & \left.\frac{\text{share}_{\text{1\ensuremath{\leftarrow}2}}+\text{share}_{\text{1\ensuremath{\rightarrow}2}}}{2}\right\rbrace ,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{12}=W_{21}$
\end_inset

 since the final network is undirected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Modularity Maximization Formula and Algorithm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to identify knowledge markets from the network constructed above,
 I employ the Louvain community detection algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "blondelFastUnfoldingCommunities2008"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This algorithm maximizes the modularity of the network, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, assigning each sector 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 to one of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
non-overlapping 
\emph default
communities 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 Accordingly, the objective function for this problem is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\max_{N}\max_{\left(c_{1},\dots,c_{N}\right)}Q\equiv\frac{1}{2\bm{W}}\sum_{ij}\left[W_{ij}-\frac{\bm{W}_{i}\bm{W}_{j}}{2\bm{W}}\right]\bm{1}\left\{ c_{i}=c_{j}\right\} ,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{ij}$
\end_inset

, weight of the edge connecting node 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, and bold variables denote other summations for ease of notation.
 In particular, I define 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{W_{i}}\equiv\sum_{k}\sum_{i}W_{ik},$
\end_inset

 as the sum of weights for edges with one end in node 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, and the sum of all weights in the network, respectively.
 The indicator 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{1}\left\{ c_{i}=c_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

 takes a value of 1 when nodes 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 belong to the same community.
 Note that the maximization is carried out both over the number of communities
 and the assignment of nodes to each community.
 This measure can be interpreted considering that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\bm{W}_{i}\bm{W}_{j}}{2\bm{W}}$
\end_inset

, is the expected number of edges that arise between nodes 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 in a random network.
 Therefore, modularity maximizes the distance between the density of linkages
 within communities 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{ij}$
\end_inset

 relative to the overall density of links that would arise randomly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since looping over all the permutations of nodes and community is numerically
 unfeasible, the Louvain algorithm follows an iterative procedure to maximize
 modularity.
 First, it assigns each node to its own community.
 Then, it repeats iteratively the following three steps:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Compute local deviations in modularity from reassigning the node to neighboring
 communities;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Assign nodes to communities following the local improvement granting the
 highest modularity increase;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Redefine a network with new communities as nodes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These steps are repeated until there is no significant improvement in modularity
 for further steps.
\end_layout

