.
 This expression immediately implies that if 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}$
\end_inset

 grows at a constant rate, so does 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Labor market clearing for R&D workers reads:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L^{RD}=\zeta\omega x_{e,\omega}\left(\mu_{e,\omega}+\mu_{e,1}\right)+\alpha_{I}\frac{\left(x_{I}\right)^{\gamma}}{\gamma}\mu_{1}.
\]

\end_inset

 In a constant growth equilibrium (CGE), the distribution is stationary,
 and since the left hand side is constant, research intensities are also
 fixed.
 A contradiction arises otherwise, since the distribution is stationary
 only if research intensities are fixed by the LOM 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: StatDist1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: statDist4"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Further, R&D labor cannot grow since the growth rate in the economy increases
 in total R&D labor for any given distribution, as it will be clear below.
 The fact that research intensities are constant immediately implies, from
 the optimality of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{e,\omega}$
\end_inset

, that 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{t}(1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{t}^{RD}$
\end_inset

 grow at the same rate.
 Indeed, from the FOC for entrants' research:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=\mathrm{d}\log x_{e,\omega,t}=\mathrm{d}\log V_{t}(1)-\mathrm{d}\log w_{t}^{RD}.
\]

\end_inset

This result in turn implies, combined with the FOC for 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{I},$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{t}(\omega)$
\end_inset

 also grows at the same constant rate.
 Now consider the budget constraint of the representative household, combined
 with product market clearing, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}=C_{t}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{t}A_{t}-\dot{A}_{t}+w_{t}^{RD}L^{RD}+w_{t}L=Y_{t},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 denote the household's assets, that is all firms in the economy.
 Therefore the above reads:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{t}\left(\mu_{1}V_{t}(1)+\mu_{\omega}V_{t}(\omega)\right)-\mu_{1}\dot{V}_{t}(1)-\mu_{\omega}\dot{V}_{t}(\omega)+w_{t}^{RD}L^{RD}+w_{t}L=Y_{t}
\]

\end_inset

Dividing both sides by 
\begin_inset Formula $V(1)$
\end_inset

, using the Euler equation and rearranging we obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(g+\rho\right)\left(\mu_{1}+\mu_{\omega}\frac{V_{t}(\omega)}{V_{t}(1)}\right)-\mu_{1}g_{V_{1}}-\mu_{\omega}\frac{V_{t}(\omega)}{V_{t}(1)}g_{V_{1}}+\frac{w_{t}^{RD}}{V_{t}(1)}L^{RD}=\frac{Y_{t}}{V_{t}(1)}-\frac{w_{t}}{V_{t}(1)}L.
\]

\end_inset

By what shown above, all terms on the left hand side are constant in 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, since research wages and values grows at the same rate and the distribution
 is stationary.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{t}$
\end_inset

 grow at the same rate positive rate, it must be that 
